Introduction¶

In [2]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns 
% matplotlib inline

The datasets which I have selected for this exploration are global indicator data taken from Gapminder World. The four indicators I have decided to explore are life expectancy, mean years of schooling, income (GDP per capita), and fertility (number of children per woman).

The questions I hope to answer are as follows:

  1. What have been the global trends regarding this four indicators in the past half-century?
  2. What are the best predictors of the life expectancy in a country?

In [29]:
combined = life[['country', '2015']].merge(income[['country', '2015']], how = 'inner', on = 'country')
combined = combined.merge(fertility[['country', '2015']], how = 'inner', on = 'country')
combined = combined.merge(meanyears[['country', '2015']], how = 'inner', on = 'country')

I create a new combined dataframe using the 2015 data for each indicator. By using an inner merge on the data, I ensure that only countries that have data for all four indicators remain in the combined dataset. I then proceed to rename the columns in the combined dataframe to match the indicator, and I set the index to the country name.

This is a time series plot of every single country's life expectancy from the year 1800 to 2018. I have also specifically highlighted several countries to see how the trends for developed/developing countries diverge.

The most interesting aspect about this graph is that there are often global phenomenae which affect the life expectancies in all countries simultaneously. The most jarring examples of this would be around 1919 and 1945, at the height of the two World Wars, during which millions of casualties led to a marked decline in life expectancies. Specifically in the case of China, we also see the effects of the cultural revolution in the 1960s, which led to a precipitous dip in life expectancies, which appears to be of greater magnitude than even the dips caused by the world war.

But it is also encouraging to see that at the turn of the century, as almost a general rule, every country has seen marked increases in their life expectancy, as a result of improved technology and healthcare. At the start of the century, most countries had a life expectancy in the range of 30 to 50 years, whereas now the range falls between 60 and 80 years; almost a doubling within the span of 100 years.

It is time to look at the correlations between the individual indicators. We will be using the 'combined' data frame, which has the 2015 data for each country for each indicator.

combined['log_income'] = np.log(combined['income'])
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 7))

sns.set_context(rc = {'font.size': 20, 'axes.labelsize': 25, 'xtick.labelsize': 25, 'ytick.labelsize': 25})
fig = sns.regplot('log_income', "life_expectancy", data = combined, ax=ax)
fig.text(8.65, 74.3, "vietnam", horizontalalignment='left', size='x-small', color='black', weight='semibold')
fig.text(6.5, 80, "Life expectancy = 5.153 * ln(income) + 24.94", horizontalalignment='left', size='x-small', color='black', weight='semibold')
ax.set_xlabel('Ln of Income')
ax.set_ylabel('Life Expectancy')
np.polyfit(combined['log_income'], combined['life_expectancy'], 1)
Out[383]:
array([ 5.15275895, 24.93425615])

y = 5.15log(x) + 24.94

I created a new column in the combined data frame to contain the natural logarithm of the income value. I then graphed this against life expectancy to derive a linear relationship. I also imported scipy to calculate the coefficients for a line of best fit.

The equation is as follows: y = 5.15log(x) + 24.94

This would suggest that the life expectancy for a given country is the natural logarithm of the income per capita, multiplied by 5.153, plus 24.94.

Conclusions¶

Ultimately, the data provided here at most suggests a series of correlations, but does not say anything about the causation between the variables.

What I have found in this exploration is that:

  • There is a linear relationship between fertility and life expectancy
  • There is a linear relationship between mean years of schooling and life expectancy
  • There is a logarithmic relationship between income per capita and life expectancy, which can be described by the equation y = 5.15log(x) + 24.94
